<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:6<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53d2682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:6.</label.designator><headtext>Privilege against self-incrimination—Privilege of the accused to remain silent</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In the second application of the right against self-incrimination the accused has the right to remain silent and not have it commented upon. <eos/><bos/>The new Evidence Code did not carry over former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36,[<footnote.reference refid="I778640b074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] which covered the effect of acquiescence or silence (tacit admissions).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ib259435274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Doyle v. Ohio</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I778640b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] the United States Supreme Court held that using an accused&apos;s silence, after receiving a <ital>Miranda</ital> warning at the time of his arrest, violates the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976136054" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25a54c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Howard v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I778667c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] a classic tacit admission case, the Georgia Supreme Court considered the effect of <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ib25bb45274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Doyle</ital></cite.query> and other cases on tacit admission. <eos/><bos/>The defendant was arrested for burglary and was taken to the victim&apos;s house for identification. <eos/><bos/>The victim said, “That&apos;s him,” and the defendant made no reply. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals approved a jury charge of former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36 based on <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1973128810" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25bb45674d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Bennett v State</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I778667c174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] The Georgia Supreme Court reversed, citing <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ib25e255274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Doyle</ital></cite.query>, <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/><?page no="93"?>“It thus is apparent that use of petitioner&apos;s silence as evidence of guilt would be unconstitutional.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> On this issue, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1973128810" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25e255674d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Bennett</ital></cite.query> and its predecessors were specifically overruled and the court stated the Georgia rule as follows: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“Restated, we hold that, in view of <ital>Miranda</ital>, police interrogation is not such a circumstance as requires an answer or denial so as to authorize charging <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-3-36" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ib25e255774d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36</cite.query> in a criminal case.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I77868ed074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1982150447" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25ee8a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Durden v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I77868ed174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court further held that, where the defendant refused to answer a specific question, even after otherwise waiving his <ital>Miranda</ital> rights in talking to police, his silence could not be used in the State&apos;s case in chief.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib260483274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Mallory v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I77868ed274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] a case decided under the old Evidence Code, the Georgia Supreme Court defined <ital>any</ital> comment on an accused&apos;s pre-arrest silence or failure to come forward as being “more prejudicial than probative” and disallowed such testimony <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“even where the defendant has not received <ital>Miranda</ital> warnings and where he takes the stand in his own defense.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7786b5e074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2001686109" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib261a7c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Morrison v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7786b5e174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals sought to clarify the <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib2626b1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Mallory</ital></cite.query> holding by stating that its application was limited to cases in which the defendant was silent <begin.quote ID="QT_0005"/>“in the face of questions by an agent of the State”<end.quote refid="QT_0005"/> or he otherwise failed <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“to come forward when he knew that he was the target of a criminal investigation.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7786b5e274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] Accordingly, the Court of Appeals held that testimony by a molestation victim&apos;s mother regarding the defendant&apos;s silence after she accused him of the crime was properly admitted under former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-26 and was not a violation of the defendant&apos;s constitutional rights because she was not an agent of the state.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7786dcf074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, this caveat was short-lived because the Georgia Supreme Court expressly overruled <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2001686109" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib2648df274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Morrison</ital></cite.query>, and similar opinions by the Court of Appeals, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2018191151" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib2648df574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Reynolds v. State</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7786dcf174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2018191151" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib267260274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Reynolds</ital></cite.query><?page no="94"?>, the Court stated that the Georgia Court of Appeals improperly limited the <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib267260574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Mallory</ital></cite.query> holding in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2001686109" w-seq-number="00039" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib267260874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Morrison</ital></cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00040" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib267260b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Mallory</ital></cite.query> was merely the recognition that the General Assembly had, by its enactment of former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36, formulated an evidentiary rule which stated that a defendant&apos;s silence or inaction will rise to the level of an admission under certain circumstances. <eos/><bos/>Since a criminal defendant&apos;s failure to speak or act will most often be judged as evidence of the admission of criminal responsibility, the element of prejudice is indisputable and a prosecutor may never properly comment on a defendant&apos;s pre-arrest silence.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7787040074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] Moreover, even if a defendant makes statements to police prior to receiving <ital>Miranda</ital> warnings, but thereafter clearly asserts his right to remain silent, any statements made after an officer continues to question the defendant are inadmissible.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7787040174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] However, it must be an unequivocal assertion that he is invoking his right to remain silent; if the defendant continues to talk, or makes statements that are equivocal, the interrogating officers have no obligation to stop the questioning.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7787040274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The bright line exclusionary rule set out in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00046" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib269be1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Mallory</ital></cite.query>, that a criminal defendant&apos;s pre-arrest silence or failure to come forward to law enforcement is always far more prejudicial than probative, was overruled by enactment of the 2013 Evidence Code. <eos/><bos/>This was the holding in the 2019 case of <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2048192082" w-seq-number="00047" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib269be1574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>State v. Orr</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77872b1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">16</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2048192082" w-seq-number="00049" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib26ddcc274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Orr,</ital></cite.query> the Supreme Court of Georgia reasoned that, under the new Evidence Code, the exclusion of evidence, an extraordinary remedy, is analyzed under a balancing test which weighs its probative value against its prejudicial effects. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-seq-number="00050" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER403" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Ib26ddcc374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rule 403</cite.query> <begin.quote ID="QT_0006"/>“provides no authority for an appellate court to direct the exclusion of entire categories of evidence.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0006"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I77872b1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">17</footnote.reference>] The Court remanded the case so that the relevant analysis could be made under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-seq-number="00052" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-403" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ib26e790074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-403</cite.query> of whether defendant&apos;s pre-arrest silence on the issue of self-defense was more probative than prejudicial.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><?page no="95"?><bos/><paratext>Violation of this rule does not always warrant reversal of a conviction. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court has explained that, while a charge pursuant to former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36 has no place in a criminal trial because it can be construed as a comment on defendant&apos;s constitutional right to remain silent, the use of a charge containing this language will not always require reversal of a conviction.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I77872b1274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">18</footnote.reference>] <begin.quote ID="QT_0008"/>“The error may be found to be harmless beyond a reasonable doubt,”<end.quote refid="QT_0008"/> and <begin.quote ID="QT_0007"/>“the determination of harmless error must be made on a case by case basis, taking into consideration the facts, the trial context of the error, and the prejudice created thereby as juxtaposed against the strength of the evidence of defendant&apos;s guilt.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0007"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7787522074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">19</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I778640b074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Repealed effective January 1, 2013.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I778640b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976142405" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ib259917274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Doyle v. Ohio, 426 U.S. 610, 96 S. Ct. 2240, 49 L. Ed. 2d 91 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I778667c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976136054" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25a7bd274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Howard v. State, 237 Ga. 471, 228 S.E.2d 860 (1976)</cite.query><?page no="93"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I778667c174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1973128810" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25c027274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bennett v. State, 231 Ga. 458, 202 S.E.2d 99 (1973)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Court of Appeals approved a jury charge that followed former O.C.G.A. § 24-3-36, Georgia&apos;s former tacit admission statute. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976143621" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25c77a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Howard v. State, 137 Ga. App. 352, 223 S.E.2d 745 (1976)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Supreme Court <case.history>overruled</case.history>, however <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976136054" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25c77a574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Howard v. State, 237 Ga. 471, 228 S.E.2d 860 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77868ed074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1976136054" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25e737274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Howard v. State, 237 Ga. 471, 228 S.E.2d 860 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77868ed174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1982150447" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25f0fb274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Durden v. State, 250 Ga. 325, 297 S.E.2d 237 (1982)</cite.query> (defendant answered several of the officer&apos;s questions after receiving <ital>Miranda</ital> warning but declined to answer one).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="2008292317" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib25f5dd274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hines v. State, 277 Ga. App. 404, 626 S.E.2d 601 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I77868ed274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018119" w-serial-number="1991182734" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ib260965274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Mallory v. State, 261 Ga. 625, 409 S.E.2d 839 (1991)</cite.query> (superseded by statute as stated